About this hotel

In a restored riad, this sophisticated hotel is within 2 km from Jemaa el-Fnaa square, the Marrakech Museum and Majorelle Garden.

    Sebastian Erikssona year ago on Google
    5/5
    Stepping into this Riad feels like stepping into the home you've always wished you had. Everything from the decor, the breakfast and the personnel seems to have been designed to give you a relaxing experience - but with intricate details …
    Stepping into this Riad feels like stepping into the home you've always wished you had. Everything from the decor, the breakfast and the personnel seems to have been designed to give you a relaxing experience - but with intricate details that keeps everything interesting. The Riad is designed so well it deserves a spot in a fashion magazine - with multiple niches where you can hang out in style and relax, great attention to detail and a very "zen flow" to the design - I don't even hesitate to call it among the top 5 establishments out of the hundreds I've visited over the years!
    We were met by the owner who gave us the warmest welcome I've experienced in any part of the world so far. Not only that, we were given updates on COVID measurements/restrictions both then AND during our stay. The vast knowledge of the staff also made sure we knew where to go, how to go there, and what to look for and avoid on the way. Everything was presented in perfect english, with a beautiful smile! The owner + staff also helped us with communicating with tour guides and similar which was greatly appreciated and helpful.
    I would, and will, recommend this place to everyone. It made our stay in the medina something truly special. Whether you're into something central, fancy, "homey" or relaxing - this is the place for you!
    Practical notes: Very clean rooms and premises (daily cleaning), varied traditional Moroccan breakfast with western extras, multilingual owner, amazing rooftop area with pool, nice and quiet, hotel shuttle (15€, more or less the same as the petite taxis), "mini-mart" close by, 10-15 min walk to the central square. Very practical overall.

    Cristina Metgher3 years ago on Google
    5/5
    Tip 1: definitely accept the ride from the airport to the hotel(offered by Riad de Vinci), 15€ but definitely worth it -- a person was waiting outside at the exit from the airport, and it took me straight to the hotel, no issues with …
    Tip 1: definitely accept the ride from the airport to the hotel(offered by Riad de Vinci), 15€ but definitely worth it -- a person was waiting outside at the exit from the airport, and it took me straight to the hotel, no issues with getting lost. Took the ride from the hotel back to the airport as well and highly recommend it.
    Tip 2: do not accept help from adults or kids promising you to show you how to get somewhere, they may ask a fee at the end or worse. Make sure you get a map from the hotel and have your map on the phone. The streets are very narrow throughout the whole city and it can be a little complicated to navigate.
    Really friendly personnel, provided a map and explained how to get around the city really well. The man at the front desk (his name is also Riad) was the most helpful, giving lots of tips on what to see around the city, where to eat, and what to pay attention to. The breakfast that was included in the price was different every day and we'll made. A cute house cat lives in the hotels but doesn't get into your room unless you invite her. Minor note about the tap, that was a little difficult to handle.

    Basil Lim3 years ago on Google
    5/5
    Awesome respite from the souk.
    Management and staff are friendly, helpful and all round awesome. Especially …
    Awesome respite from the souk.
    Management and staff are friendly, helpful and all round awesome. Especially Ayyoub, the night porter, he helped us order pizzas and gave loads of advice. The riad's cat, Da Vinci is also a super chill and friendly cat.
    You can order massages/hammam directly in the riad (has an attached spa) and also excursions, they organise everything and contact a driver for you.
    Just be warned on excursions to bring extra cash, everything costs money, for example, when we went to Imlil we had to pay an extra 200 dirhams for a guide (which you'll need) and 120 per person for lunch - this was well worth it, but isn't mentioned in the initial cost of the trip.
    Great terrace where you can order beers or mint tea and look out at the city - you won't see the square from here but you actually won't want to, it's quieter here. You can even get lunch or dinner although choice is limited.
    Breakfast is awesome, fresh orange juice, mint tea or coffee, bread jam and crepes/cake as well as a delicious yogurt.
    It's a little hard to get to due to confusing alleyways, but the first night if you get an airport transfer, they'll have a guide to get you there. It's not too difficult, but can be a bit confusing initially.
    Highly recommended

    Medina

    Hammam bath houses and covered spice and textile souks line the maze of cobblestoned lanes in the Medina, which occupies Marrakesh’s original fortified citadel. At night, Jemaa el-Fna square teems with snake charmers, folk dancers, and street food vendors serving all manner of food. Bahia Palace and Le Jardin Secret are 19th-century complexes open to the public, with ornate courtyards, mosaics, and gardens.

    About this hotel

    In a restored riad, this sophisticated hotel is within 2 km from Jemaa el-Fnaa square, the Marrakech Museum and Majorelle Garden. …

    Refined rooms offer elaborate bathrooms (some partially open), while upgraded rooms add terraces or balconies.

    The 3 courtyards feature pools and sitting areas. A serene adjoining spa offers hammams, massages and beauty treatments. There's also a rooftop sundeck, which has city views.
